Introduction¶

I worked on TMDb movie dataset that is found on kaggle , which provides data on movies from (1960 - 2015) with many attributes and more than 10000 movie record.¶

After choosing the dataset and understanding the attributes well , I decided to ask three questions¶

Q1: Which genres are mostly released each year ?¶

Q2: Which columns are associated with (has impact on) Net_profit column (Revenue - Budget) ?¶

Q3: Does Genres contribute in the popularity of the movie? which genre has the highest impact on popularity?¶

Since they are multiple genres for each movie , so we will make a boolean column for each unique genre (one hot encoding) in order that we can use genre column in our analysis and insights.¶

In [16]:
## this function takes a column and generetes new columns for each unique value within the column and makes one hot encoding
def one_hot_encoding(genres_col):   
    gender_df=genres_col.str.split('|',expand=True).stack()
    gender_df=pd.get_dummies(gender_df,prefix='G').groupby(level=0).sum()
    return gender_df
In [17]:

Data Cleaning¶

Here we gonna drop columns that are not useful during our analysis process , and also columns that contains alot of Null values , Fortunately the columns that has many Nulls are not useful in analysis so they will be dropped¶

Here also budget_adj and revenue_adj are dropped because i will use budget and revenue in my analysis instead , as they both refer to the same thing but adj accounts for inflation over time¶

In [21]:
df.drop(['id','imdb_id','original_title','homepage','director','tagline','keywords','overview','production_companies'
         ,'release_date','budget_adj','revenue_adj'],axis='columns',inplace=True)

Genres and cast columns have few NaN values , these columns contains strings so they can't be imputed from other values , so the best ways to deal with this NaN values is to delete their records since they are few¶

After deleting the Records that has NaN in genres we will delete genres column as we already substituted it with dummy columns for each unique genre¶

In [22]:
df.dropna(subset=['genres','cast'],how='any',inplace=True)
df.drop(['genres'],axis='columns',inplace=True)

As discussed before it is meaningless to have budget and revenue with zero values , As there is no movie that costs zero to be produced and also there is no movie that doesn't get any revenue , I will deal with these zero values by dropping any record that has zero values in either budget or revenue¶

In [23]:
index_names=df[(df['budget']==0) | (df['revenue']==0)].index
df.drop(index_names,inplace=True)

In our analysis we will use only the net (the difference between revenue and budget) , so we will add a new column called net_profit and remove budget and revenue columns¶

In [24]:
df['net_profit']=df['revenue']-df['budget']
df.drop(['budget','revenue'],axis='columns',inplace=True)

Since that we found that there is a duplicated row when assessing the dataset , so we must drop this record¶

df.drop_duplicates(inplace=True)

Exploratory Data Analysis¶

Q1: Which genres are mostly released each year ?¶

In [28]:
genres_list=[x  for x in df.columns if 'G_' in x]

for idx in range(0,df['release_year'].nunique()):   ## to iterate on the number of unique years (from 1960-2015)
    index=df.groupby('release_year')[genres_list].mean().iloc[idx].index
    value=df.groupby('release_year')[genres_list].mean().iloc[idx].values
    plt.bar(index , value);
    plt.xticks(rotation=90)
    plt.suptitle(str(df['release_year'].min()+idx))
    plt.xlabel('Genres')
    plt.ylabel('Frequency')
    plt.show()

The cell above shows plots for each year (1960 - 2015) , these plots shows which was the common genre at each year , for example in the first plot (1960) we can see that the most movies released in 1960 was characterized as drama genre¶

Q3: Does Genres contribute in the popularity of the movie? which genre has the highest impact on popularity?¶

In [40]:
plt.rcParams["figure.figsize"]=(15,15);
genres_list=[x  for x in df.columns if 'G_' in x]

idx=0
x_axis=[]
for genre in genres_list:
    #plt.xticks(label='aa')   
    plt.bar(idx,df.groupby(genre)['popularity'].mean().values[1]);
    x_axis.append(idx);
    idx=idx+1
plt.xticks(x_axis,genres_list,rotation=90);
plt.title('Genres Vs Popularity',size=20);
plt.xlabel('Genres',size=20);
plt.ylabel('Popularity',size=20);

The figure above shows how the genres affects the popularity , we can see that adventure and science fiction genres has the highest popularity among all genres , while genre as foreign and documentary and tv movie doesn't have high popularity compared to other genres¶

Conclusions¶

From the first question we can see which genre is mostly included in movies each year , In nutshell we can notice by looking at the different bar charts for each year that the most common genre over most of the years was drama, but not the case in all years¶

From the second question we can see that there is strong association between popularity and Net profit which means when popularity increases it leads to increase in Net profit , there is also weak correlation between both average voting and runtime with net profit , we also can see from the bar chart between release year and net profit that the net profit increases somehow over years and that also makes sense.¶

From the third question we can conclude that the genres with the highest popularity are science fiction and adventure , We also can conclude that despite the drama genre was the most released over years as discussed in question one but it didn't get a high popularity compared to other genres¶

Limitations¶

We have neglected the cast column in our analysis , despite that it is useful as the actor will effect the revenue of the movie , but we had to neglect it because during analysis we found that there is many unique actors more than 5000 actor , so if we made dummy columns for actors as we made with genre column , the dimensions of the dataframe will increase so much¶

We have dropped any row that contain zero budget or revenue which led to dropping about half of the rows of our dataset¶

There wasn't currency provided with the revenue and budget column , so they were all treated the same as if they all were the same currency¶
